observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to:

Require the SI to properly store and transfer the vials and other COVID-19 vaccination wastes together with the consolidated Form A – Reverse Logistic, supported with DENR Manifest Form to PHO every Friday of the vaccination week; 
Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that received, issued and balance of COVID-19 vaccines are disclosures in the Notes Financial Statements; and

Require the Property Custodian to:

Use the Acknowledge Receipt for In-Kind Donations for DRRM and Issuance form for In-Kind Donations-DRRM for the receipt and issuance of COVID-19 vaccines;
Prepare and maintain the Registry of Donated Relief Goods for DRRM and Inventory Report-DRRM for the receipt and utilization of COVID-19 Vaccines;
Prepare and submit to Office of the Civil Defense (OCD), Auditor of the OCD and to COA Auditor, the Monthly Report on the Receipt and Distribution/Issuance of Donated Relief Goods for the received COVID-19 vaccines;
Prepare and submit the monthly Inventory List of Items for DRRM supported with the required documents to COA and to Municipal Accounting Office.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:  

a) Municipal Accountant – Designate to prepare and maintain SLCs for Inventories Held for Distribution and other inventory items; to coordinate with the Property Custodian – Designate and other offices concerned to ascertain the accuracy and existence of the inventory account balances; and to prepare the necessary adjusting entries;  

b) Property Custodian – Designate and other offices concerned to comply with the provisions of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs on recording of receipts and issuances of inventories, the maintenance of stock cards, and the use of RIS for issuances and the preparation of monthly RSMIs based on RISs and the submission of copies thereof to the Municipal Accountant – Designate for recording;  

c) Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of inventories on a semestral basis, reconcile the result of physical count with the property and the accounting records, and prepare and submit a copy of the RPCI to the Audit Team within the reglementary period, pursuant to the pertinent provisions of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require the Municipal Accountant to:
Include disclosure in the Notes to FS regarding changes in accounting policies in accordance with the applicable provisions of IPSAS 3;
Include disclosures in the Notes to FS regarding changes in accounting policies, specifically those which are adopted from circulars issued by the Commission on Audit such as COA Circular No. 2022-004;
Ensure inclusion of comparative information for Aging/Analysis of Receivables and Additions/Deletions for PPE Accounts in the Notes to FS; and
Ensure that the amounts between condensed/detailed FS, the Notes to FS, and those within the face of the FS are tallied.

We recommended that the management:
create an Inventory Committee, who are temporarily relieved of all their regular duties, to complete the physical inventory in three (3) months or less;
prepare and submit the approved Physical Inventory Plan to the COA Audit Team at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities;
ensure full implementation of "One-time cleansing of PPE accounts" as provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006 in order to address the unlocated and unreconciled PPEs;
require the Municipal Assessor to:
obtain records/ documents pertaining to the acquisition of the unrecorded land with a total market value of ₱1,899,640.00;
require the Municipal Engineer to:
coordinate with the Office of the Municipal Accountant and OIC- Property Custodian for the determination of the cost and age of the replaced parts of the infrastructure assets for proper recording; and
require the Municipal Accountant to:
prepare adjusting journal entries to record the unrecorded parcels of land with a total market value of ₱1,899,640.00;
investigate the replaced parts of the infrastructure assets and prepare a journal entry to derecognize the replaced parts, if any, in accordance with IPSAS and PAG; and
exert effort to trace prior years’ records and determine the unidentified balances of CIP accounts amounting to ₱4,955,228.02.

We recommended that the management:
Create an Inventory Committee to conduct annual physical count of local road networks and to submit the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network not later than January 31 of each year;
Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the OIC-Property Custodian with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
Require the Municipal Accountant to present in the Notes to Financial Statements the required disclosure for local road networks, and to prepare and maintain Local Road Network Ledger Cards for each local road; and
Require the OIC-Property Custodian / Property Unit to prepare the annual Report of Local Road Network, and to prepare and maintain the Local Road Network Property Cards for each local road.

We recommended that the LCE:
Require the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and the Program. Project, Activity (PPAs) Focal Persons to review the financial records, statements, and prior years’ transactions in order to track the history and origin of the fund transfers totaling ₱3,107,790.61;
Require the Municipal Accountant to conduct confirmation of the balance of unliquidated fund transfers from source NGAs that granted assistance to LGUs in order to reconcile the balances of fund transfers;
Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to immediately submit to COA Audit Team the DVs with the corresponding supporting documents for disbursements totaling ₱5,954,039.82. for audit and verification.
Require the BAC Secretariat to ensure submission the perfected contracts and its supporting documents within five (5) working days from its execution; and
Assess and review the necessity and feasibility of the PPAs funded by NGAs through fund transfer; otherwise, return the funds to the source agencies.

Require the Supply Officer/ General Services Officer and the Municipal Health Officer to account for any unutilized balance of the received medicines and medical supplies from DOH and submit to the Municipal Accountant for recording of the appropriate amount of asset, income and expense as of year end;
Create a committee for the appraisal of the in-kind donations without cost for proper recording in the books of accounts;
Require all the recipient offices, through the Supply Officer, to record all receipts of in-kind donations for monitoring purposes.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:  

a) Municipal Accountant – Designate to prepare and maintain SLCs for Inventories Held for Distribution and other inventory items; to coordinate with the Property Custodian – Designate and other offices concerned to ascertain the accuracy and existence of the inventory account balances; and to prepare the necessary adjusting entries;  

b) Property Custodian – Designate and other offices concerned to comply with the provisions of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs on recording of receipts and issuances of inventories, the maintenance of stock cards, and the use of RIS for issuances and the preparation of monthly RSMIs based on RISs and the submission of copies thereof to the Municipal Accountant – Designate for recording;  

c) Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of inventories on a semestral basis, reconcile the result of physical count with the property and the accounting records, and prepare and submit a copy of the RPCI to the Audit Team within the reglementary period, pursuant to the pertinent provisions of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended that the LCE oblige:

 a) the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to ascertain and immediately release the respective shares of the barangays from RPT collections;

Henceforth, remit the shares of barangays from Real Property Tax collections regularly, pursuant to Section 271(d), Chapter VII, Title II of RA No. 7160.

We recommended and Management agreed, that the LCE direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Enforce the immediate liquidation of the unliquidated cash advances by regularly sending demand letters and to refrain from granting additional cash advance to officials and employees with outstanding balances until the previous cash advances are fully settled /liquidated;
Designate a staff to closely monitor the liquidation of outstanding cash;
Determine the unliquidated cash advances that are non-moving for more than ten years where settlement/collectability could no longer be ascertained and initiate the request for write-off as allowed under Item 7.0 of COA Circular No. 2016-005; and
Submit immediately the liquidation reports and complete supporting documents to the Audit Team for review and verification.

We recommended and Management agreed, that the LCE:
Require the Supply Officer/ General Services Officer and the Municipal Health Officer to account for any unutilized balance of the received medicines and medical supplies from DOH and submit to the Municipal Accountant for recording of the appropriate amount of asset, income and expense as of year end;
Create a committee for the appraisal of the in-kind donations without cost for proper recording in the books of accounts;
Require all the recipient offices, through the Supply Officer, to record all receipts of in-kind donations for monitoring purposes.

We recommended and Management agreed, that the LCE require the concerned MHO personnel to submit immediately to the audit team, thru the Accountant, the following documents to establish their claim to SRAs under AO Nos. 36 and 42:
Authority for the entitlement of the allowance/ office order/ authority to  report for work;
Daily Time Records with Biometric printouts/copies of logbook or Certificate of Attendance in the COVID Facility/Center by their immediate supervisor during the period of claims;
Accomplishment reports indicating the number of COVID patients attended to in a day.
For health workers not directly catering COVID-19 patients, an explanation as to the scientific basis for the premise that healthcare workers not directly catering to COVID-19 patients are equally exposed to COVID-19 and can be considered “in contact with COVID-19 patients”, and thus should be given the SRA

We recommended that the LCE:
require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to revert back to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund the unutilized LDRRMF continuing appropriation in CY 2011 amounting to P523,122.59;
cause the enactment by the local sanggunian of an ordinance for the subsequent use of the amount of P523,122.59;

We also recommended that management transfer immediately to STF the remaining unexpended balance of P296,233.88.  Henceforth, ensure that the LDRRMF is utilized and managed properly, pursuant to RA No. 10121 and COA Circular No. 2012-002.
